# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The **Barabási–Albert (BA) model** is an algorithm for generating random scale-free networks using a preferential attachment mechanism.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Several natural and human-made systems, including the Internet, the World Wide Web, citation networks, and some social networks are thought to be approximately scale-free and certainly contain few nodes (called hubs) with unusually high degree as compared to the other nodes of the network.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The BA model tries to explain the existence of such nodes in real networks.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The algorithm is named for its inventors Albert-László Barabási and Réka Albert.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Many observed networks (at least approximately) fall into the class of scale-free networks, meaning that they have power-law (or scale-free) degree distributions, while random graph models such as the Erdős–Rényi (ER) model and the Watts–Strogatz (WS) model do not exhibit power laws.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The Barabási–Albert model is one of several proposed models that generate scale-free networks.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] It incorporates two important general concepts: growth and preferential attachment.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Both growth and preferential attachment exist widely in real networks.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Growth means that the number of nodes in the network increases over time.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Preferential attachment means that the more connected a node is, the more likely it is to receive new links.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Nodes with a higher degree have a stronger ability to grab links added to the network.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Intuitively, the preferential attachment can be understood if we think in terms of social networks connecting people.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Here a link from A to B means that person A "knows" or "is acquainted with" person B.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Heavily linked nodes represent well-known people with lots of relations.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] When a newcomer enters the community, they are more likely to become acquainted with one of those more visible people rather than with a relative unknown.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The BA model was proposed by assuming that in the World Wide Web, new pages link preferentially to hubs, i.e. very well known sites such as Google, rather than to pages that hardly anyone knows.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] If someone selects a new page to link to by randomly choosing an existing link, the probability of selecting a particular page would be proportional to its degree.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The BA model claims that this explains the preferential attachment probability rule.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Later, the Bianconi–Barabási model works to address this issue by introducing a "fitness" parameter.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Preferential attachment is an example of a positive feedback cycle where initially random variations (one node initially having more links or having started accumulating links earlier than another) are automatically reinforced, thus greatly magnifying differences.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] This is also sometimes called the Matthew effect, "the rich get richer".
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The only parameter in the BA model is m , a positive integer.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The network initializes with a network of $m_{0}\geq m$ nodes.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] where $k_{i}$ is the degree of node i and the sum is made over all pre-existing nodes j (i.e. the denominator results in twice the current number of edges in the network).
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] This step can be performed by first uniformly sampling one edge, then sampling one of the two vertices on the edge.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Heavily linked nodes ("hubs") tend to quickly accumulate even more links, while nodes with only a few links are unlikely to be chosen as the destination for a new link.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The new nodes have a "preference" to attach themselves to the already heavily linked nodes.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Correlations between the degrees of connected nodes develop spontaneously in the BA model because of the way the network evolves.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] This confirms the existence of degree correlations, because if the distributions were uncorrelated, we would get $n_{k\ell }=k^{-3}\ell ^{-3}$ .
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] In other words, if we select a node with degree k , and then select one of its neighbors randomly, the probability that this randomly selected neighbor will have degree $\ell$ is given by the expression $p(\ell |k)$ above.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The case for $m=1$ is trivial: networks are trees and the clustering coefficient is equal to zero.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] An analytical result for the clustering coefficient of the BA model was obtained by Klemm and Eguíluz and proven by Bollobás.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] A mean-field approach to study the clustering coefficient was applied by Fronczak, Fronczak and Holyst.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] This behavior is distinct from the behavior of small-world networks where clustering is independent of system size.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The clustering as a function of node degree $C(k)$ is practically independent of k .
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The spectral density of BA model has a different shape from the semicircular spectral density of random graph.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] It has a triangle-like shape with the top lying well above the semicircle and edges decaying as a power law.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] In (Section 5.1), it was proved that the shape of this spectral density is not an exact triangular function by analyzing the moments of the spectral density as a function of the power-law exponent.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Model A retains growth but does not include preferential attachment.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The probability of a new node connecting to any pre-existing node is equal.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The resulting degree distribution in this limit is geometric, indicating that growth alone is not sufficient to produce a scale-free structure.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Model B retains preferential attachment but eliminates growth.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The model begins with a fixed number of disconnected nodes and adds links, preferentially choosing high degree nodes as link destinations.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Though the degree distribution early in the simulation looks scale-free, the distribution is not stable, and it eventually becomes nearly Gaussian as the network nears saturation.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] So preferential attachment alone is not sufficient to produce a scale-free structure.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The failure of models A and B to lead to a scale-free distribution indicates that growth and preferential attachment are needed simultaneously to reproduce the stationary power-law distribution observed in real networks.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The BA model can be thought of as a specific case of the more general non-linear preferential attachment (NLPA) model.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] where $\alpha$ is a constant positive exponent.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] If $\alpha =1$ , NLPA reduces to the BA model and is referred to as "linear".
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] If $0<\alpha <1$ , NLPA is referred to as "sub-linear" and the degree distribution of the network tends to a stretched exponential distribution.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] If $\alpha >1$ , NLPA is referred to as "super-linear" and a small number of nodes connect to almost all other nodes in the network.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] For both $\alpha <1$ and $\alpha >1$ , the scale-free property of the network is broken in the limit of infinite system size.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] However, if $\alpha$ is only slightly larger than 1 , NLPA may result in degree distributions which appear to be transiently scale free.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Preferential attachment made its first appearance in 1923 in the celebrated urn model of the Hungarian mathematician György Pólya in 1923.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] The master equation method, which yields a more transparent derivation, was applied to the problem by Herbert A.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Simon in 1955 in the course of studies of the sizes of cities and other phenomena.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] It was first applied to explain citation frequencies by Derek de Solla Price in 1976.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] Price was interested in the accumulation of citations of scientific papers and the Price model used "cumulative advantage" (his name for preferential attachment) to generate a fat tailed distribution.
[src:network-science/barabási-albert-model] In the language of modern citations network, Price's model produces a directed network, i.e. the version of the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] In graph theory, **betweenness centrality** is a measure of centrality in a graph based on shortest paths.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Betweenness centrality measures how frequently a node appears on the shortest path between other nodes in the graph.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Betweenness centrality was devised as a general measure of centrality:.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] It applies to a wide range of problems in network theory, including problems related to social networks, biology, transport, and scientific cooperation.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Although earlier authors had intuitively described centrality in terms of betweenness, Freeman (1977) gave the first formal definition of betweenness centrality.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Betweenness centrality has wide application in network theory; it measures the extent to which nodes lie between one another.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] For example, in a telecommunications network, a node with higher betweenness centrality would have more control over the network because more information flows through it.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] where $\sigma _{st}$ is the total number of shortest paths from node s to node t and $\sigma _{st}(v)$ is the number of those paths that pass through v (not where v is an end point).
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The betweenness centrality of a node scales with the number of pairs of nodes as suggested by the summation indices.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Therefore, the calculation may be rescaled by dividing through by the number of pairs of nodes not including v , so that $g\in [0,1]$ .
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The division is done by $(N-1)(N-2)$ for directed graphs and $(N-1)(N-2)/2$ for undirected graphs, where N is the number of nodes in the giant component.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Note that this scales for the highest possible value, where one node is crossed by every single shortest path.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Note that this will always be a scaling from a smaller range into a larger range, so no precision is lost.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] In a weighted network the links connecting the nodes are no longer treated as binary interactions, but are weighted in proportion to their capacity, influence, frequency, etc., which adds another dimension of heterogeneity within the network beyond the topological effects.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] A node's strength in a weighted network is given by the sum of the weights of its adjacent edges.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] With $a_{ij}$ and $w_{ij}$ being adjacency and weight matrices between nodes i and j , respectively.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Analogous to the power law distribution of degree found in scale free networks, the strength of a given node follows a power law distribution as well.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Percolation centrality is a version of weighted betweenness centrality, but it considers the 'state' of the source and target nodes of each shortest path in calculating this weight.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Percolation of a 'contagion' occurs in complex networks in a number of scenarios.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] For example, viral or bacterial infection can spread over social networks of people, known as contact networks.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The spread of disease can also be considered at a higher level of abstraction, by contemplating a network of towns or population centres, connected by road, rail or air links.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Computer viruses can spread over computer networks.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Rumours or news about business offers and deals can also spread via social networks of people.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] In all of these scenarios, a 'contagion' spreads over the links of a complex network, altering the 'states' of the nodes as it spreads, either recoverably or otherwise.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] For example, in an epidemiological scenario, individuals go from 'susceptible' to 'infected' state as the infection spreads.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The states the individual nodes can take in the above examples could be binary (such as received/not received a piece of news), discrete (susceptible/infected/recovered), or even continuous (such as the proportion of infected people in a town), as the contagion spreads.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The common feature in all these scenarios is that the spread of contagion results in the change of node states in networks.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Percolation centrality (PC) was proposed with this in mind, which specifically measures the importance of nodes in terms of aiding the percolation through the network.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] This measure was proposed by Piraveenan, Prokopenko & Hossain (2013).
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Percolation centrality is defined for a given node, at a given time, as the proportion of 'percolated paths' that go through that node.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] A 'percolated path' is a shortest path between a pair of nodes, where the source node is percolated (e.g., infected).
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The target node can be percolated or non-percolated, or in a partially percolated state.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] where $\sigma _{sr}$ is total number of shortest paths from node s to node r and $\sigma _{sr}(v)$ is the number of those paths that pass through v .
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The percolation state of the node i at time t is denoted by ${x^{t}}_{i}$ and two special cases are when ${x^{t}}_{i}=0$ which indicates a non-percolated state at time t whereas when ${x^{t}}_{i}=1$ which indicates a fully percolated state at time t .
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The values in between indicate partially percolated states ( e.g., in a network of townships, this would be the percentage of people infected in that town).
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The attached weights to the percolation paths depend on the percolation levels assigned to the source nodes, based on the premise that the higher the percolation level of a source node is, the more important are the paths that originate from that node.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Nodes which lie on shortest paths originating from highly percolated nodes are therefore potentially more important to the percolation.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The definition of PC may also be extended to include target node weights as well.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Percolation centrality calculations run in $O(|V||E|)$ time with an efficient implementation adapted from Brandes' algorithm.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] If the calculation needs to consider target node weights, the worst case time is $O(|V|^{3})$ .
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] On a sparse graph, Johnson's algorithm or Brandes' algorithm may be more efficient, both taking $O(|V|^{2}\log |V|+|V||E|)$ time.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] On unweighted graphs, calculating betweenness centrality takes $O(|V||E|)$ time using Brandes' algorithm.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] In calculating betweenness and closeness centralities of all vertices in a graph, it is assumed that graphs are undirected and connected with the allowance of loops and multiple edges.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] When specifically dealing with network graphs, often graphs are without loops or multiple edges to maintain simple relationships (where edges represent connections between two people or vertices).
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] In this case, using Brandes' algorithm will divide final centrality scores by 2 to account for each shortest path being counted twice.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Another algorithm generalizes the Freeman's betweenness computed on geodesics and Newman's betweenness computed on all paths, by introducing a hyper-parameter controlling the trade-off between exploration and exploitation.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] The time complexity is the number of edges times the number of nodes in the graph.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Because exact computation of betweenness centrality can be expensive on large graphs, a number of approximation algorithms have been proposed.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Many methods estimate betweenness by sampling shortest paths between randomly selected pairs of vertices instead of enumerating all shortest paths.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Riondato and Kornaropoulos proposed a shortest-path sampling algorithm with probabilistic error guarantees based on Vapnik–Chervonenkis theory.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Later methods such as ABRA and SILVAN used progressive sampling strategies and Rademacher averages to adaptively determine the number of sampled shortest paths needed to achieve a target accuracy.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] KADABRA is an adaptive approximation algorithm that combines shortest-path sampling with bidirectional breadth-first search and confidence interval estimation.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Local heuristics have also been proposed as computationally inexpensive alternatives.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Ego betweenness computes the betweenness of a vertex within its ego network, consisting only of the vertex, its neighbors, and the edges among those neighbors.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Other lightweight proxy measures, such as the local clustering coefficient-dependent degree centrality (LCCDC), use only local structural properties such as degree and the clustering coefficient to estimate the relative importance of vertices.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] In social network analysis, betweenness centrality can have different implications.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] From a macroscopic perspective, bridging positions or "structural holes" (indicated by high betweenness centrality) reflect power, because they allow the person on the bridging position to exercise control (e.g., decide whether to share information or not) over the persons it connects between.
[src:network-science/betweenness-centrality] Betweenness centrality has been used to analyze the topological complexity of river networks as well as their use in maritime trade.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In the study of complex networks, a network is said to have **community structure** if the nodes of the network can be easily grouped into (potentially overlapping) sets of nodes such that each set of nodes is densely connected internally.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In the particular case of *non-overlapping* community finding, this implies that the network divides naturally into groups of nodes with dense connections internally and sparser connections between groups.
[src:network-science/community-structure] But *overlapping* communities are also allowed.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The more general definition is based on the principle that pairs of nodes are more likely to be connected if they are both members of the same community(ies), and less likely to be connected if they do not share communities.
[src:network-science/community-structure] A related but different problem is community search, where the goal is to find a community that a certain vertex belongs to.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In the study of networks, such as computer and information networks, social networks and biological networks, a number of different characteristics have been found to occur commonly, including the small-world property, heavy-tailed degree distributions, and clustering, among others.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Another common characteristic is community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In the context of networks, community structure refers to the occurrence of groups of nodes in a network that are more densely connected internally than with the rest of the network, as shown in the example image to the right.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This inhomogeneity of connections suggests that the network has certain natural divisions within it.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Communities are often defined in terms of the partition of the set of vertices, that is each node is put into one and only one community, just as in the figure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This is a useful simplification and most community detection methods find this type of community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] However, in some cases a better representation could be one where vertices are in more than one community.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This might happen in a social network where each vertex represents a person, and the communities represent the different groups of friends: one community for family, another community for co-workers, one for friends in the same sports club, and so on.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The use of cliques for community detection discussed below is just one example of how such overlapping community structure can be found.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Some networks may not have any meaningful community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Many basic network models, for example, such as the random graph and the Barabási–Albert model, do not display community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Community structures are quite common in real networks.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Social networks include community groups (the origin of the term, in fact) based on common location, interests, occupation, etc.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Finding an underlying community structure in a network, if it exists, is important for a number of reasons.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Communities allow us to create a large scale map of a network since individual communities act like meta-nodes in the network which makes its study easier.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Individual communities also shed light on the function of the system represented by the network since communities often correspond to functional units of the system.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In metabolic networks, such functional groups correspond to cycles or pathways whereas in the protein interaction network, communities correspond to proteins with similar functionality inside a biological cell.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Similarly, citation networks form communities by research topic.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Being able to identify these sub-structures within a network can provide insight into how network function and topology affect each other.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Such insight can be useful in improving some algorithms on graphs such as spectral clustering.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Importantly, communities often have very different properties than the average properties of the networks.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Thus, only concentrating on the average properties usually misses many important and interesting features inside the networks.
[src:network-science/community-structure] For example, in a given social network, both gregarious and reticent groups might exists simultaneously.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Existence of communities also generally affects various processes like rumour spreading or epidemic spreading happening on a network.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Hence to properly understand such processes, it is important to detect communities and also to study how they affect the spreading processes in various settings.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Finally, an important application that community detection has found in network science is the prediction of missing links and the identification of false links in the network.
[src:network-science/community-structure] During the measurement process, some links may not get observed for a number of reasons.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Similarly, some links could falsely enter into the data because of the errors in the measurement.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Both these cases are well handled by community detection algorithm since it allows one to assign the probability of existence of an edge between a given pair of nodes.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Finding communities within an arbitrary network can be a computationally difficult task.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The number of communities, if any, within the network is typically unknown and the communities are often of unequal size and/or density.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Despite these difficulties, however, several methods for community finding have been developed and employed with varying levels of success.
[src:network-science/community-structure] One of the oldest algorithms for dividing networks into parts is the minimum cut method (and variants such as ratio cut and normalized cut).
[src:network-science/community-structure] This method sees use, for example, in load balancing for parallel computing in order to minimize communication between processor nodes.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In the minimum-cut method, the network is divided into a predetermined number of parts, usually of approximately the same size, chosen such that the number of edges between groups is minimized.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The method works well in many of the applications for which it was originally intended but is less than ideal for finding community structure in general networks since it will find communities regardless of whether they are implicit in the structure, and it will find only a fixed number of them.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Another method for finding community structures in networks is hierarchical clustering.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In this method one defines a similarity measure quantifying some (usually topological) type of similarity between node pairs.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Commonly used measures include the cosine similarity, the Jaccard index, and the Hamming distance between rows of the adjacency matrix.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Then one groups similar nodes into communities according to this measure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] An important step is how to determine the threshold to stop the agglomerative clustering, indicating a near-to-optimal community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] A common strategy consist to build one or several metrics monitoring global properties of the network, which peak at given step of the clustering.
[src:network-science/community-structure] An interesting approach in this direction is the use of various similarity or dissimilarity measures, combined through convex sums.
[src:network-science/community-structure] These methods can be extended to consider multidimensional networks, for instance when we are dealing with networks having nodes with different types of links.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Another commonly used algorithm for finding communities is the Girvan–Newman algorithm.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This algorithm identifies edges in a network that lie between communities and then removes them, leaving behind just the communities themselves.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The identification is performed by employing the graph-theoretic measure betweenness centrality, which assigns a number to each edge which is large if the edge lies "between" many pairs of nodes.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The Girvan–Newman algorithm returns results of reasonable quality and is popular because it has been implemented in a number of standard software packages.
[src:network-science/community-structure] But it also runs slowly, taking time O(*m*2*n*) on a network of *n* vertices and *m* edges, making it impractical for networks of more than a few thousand nodes.
[src:network-science/community-structure] In spite of its known drawbacks, one of the most widely used methods for community detection is modularity maximization.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Modularity is a benefit function that measures the quality of a particular division of a network into communities.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The modularity maximization method detects communities by searching over possible divisions of a network for one or more that have particularly high modularity.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Since exhaustive search over all possible divisions is usually intractable, practical algorithms are based on approximate optimization methods such as greedy algorithms, simulated annealing, or spectral optimization, with different approaches offering different balances between speed and accuracy.
[src:network-science/community-structure] A popular modularity maximization approach is the Louvain method, which iteratively optimizes local communities until global modularity can no longer be improved given perturbations to the current community state.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Methods based on statistical inference attempt to fit a generative model to the network data, which encodes the community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The overall advantage of this approach compared to the alternatives is its more principled nature, and the capacity to inherently address issues of statistical significance.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Most methods in the literature are based on the stochastic block model as well as variants including mixed membership, degree-correction, and hierarchical structures.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Model selection can be performed using principled approaches such as minimum description length (or equivalently, Bayesian model selection) and likelihood-ratio test.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Currently many algorithms exist to perform efficient inference of stochastic block models, including belief propagation and agglomerative Monte Carlo.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Cliques are subgraphs in which every node is connected to every other node in the clique.
[src:network-science/community-structure] As nodes can not be more tightly connected than this, it is not surprising that there are many approaches to community detection in networks based on the detection of cliques in a graph and the analysis of how these overlap.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Note that as a node can be a member of more than one clique, a node can be a member of more than one community in these methods giving an "*overlapping community structure*".
[src:network-science/community-structure] One approach is to find the "*maximal cliques*".
[src:network-science/community-structure] That is to find the cliques which are not the subgraph of any other clique.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The classic algorithm to find these is the Bron–Kerbosch algorithm.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The overlap of these can be used to define communities in several ways.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The simplest is to consider only maximal cliques bigger than a minimum size (number of nodes).
[src:network-science/community-structure] The union of these cliques then defines a subgraph whose components (disconnected parts) then define communities.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Such approaches are often implemented in social network analysis software such as UCInet.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The alternative approach is to use cliques of fixed size k .
[src:network-science/community-structure] The overlap of these can be used to define a type of k -regular hypergraph or a structure which is a generalisation of the line graph (the case when $k=2$ ) known as a "*Clique graph*".
[src:network-science/community-structure] The clique graphs have vertices which represent the cliques in the original graph while the edges of the clique graph record the overlap of the clique in the original graph.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Applying any of the previous community detection methods (which assign each node to a community) to the clique graph then assigns each clique to a community.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This can then be used to determine community membership of nodes in the cliques.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Again as a node may be in several cliques, it can be a member of several communities.
[src:network-science/community-structure] For instance the clique percolation method defines communities as percolation clusters of k -cliques.
[src:network-science/community-structure] To do this it finds all k -cliques in a network, that is all the complete sub-graphs of k -nodes.
[src:network-science/community-structure] It then defines two k -cliques to be adjacent if they share $k-1$ nodes, that is this is used to define edges in a clique graph.
[src:network-science/community-structure] A community is then defined to be the maximal union of k -cliques in which we can reach any k -clique from any other k -clique through series of k -clique adjacencies.
[src:network-science/community-structure] That is communities are just the connected components in the clique graph.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Since a node can belong to several different k -clique percolation clusters at the same time, the communities can overlap with each other.
[src:network-science/community-structure] A network can be represented or projected onto a latent space via representation learning methods to efficiently represent a system.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Then, various clustering methods can be employed to detect community structures.
[src:network-science/community-structure] For Euclidean spaces, methods like embedding-based Silhouette community detection can be utilized.
[src:network-science/community-structure] For Hypergeometric latent spaces, critical gap method or modified density-based, hierarchical, or partitioning-based clustering methods can be utilized.
[src:network-science/community-structure] The evaluation of algorithms, to detect which are better at detecting community structure, is still an open question.
[src:network-science/community-structure] It must be based on analyses of networks of known structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] A typical example is the "four groups" test, in which a network is divided into four equally-sized groups (usually of 32 nodes each) and the probabilities of connection within and between groups varied to create more or less challenging structures for the detection algorithm.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Such benchmark graphs are a special case of the planted l-partition model of Condon and Karp, or more generally of "stochastic block models", a general class of random network models containing community structure.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Commonly used computer-generated benchmarks start with a network of well-defined communities.
[src:network-science/community-structure] Then, this structure is degraded by rewiring or removing links and it gets harder and harder for the algorithms to detect the original partition.
[src:network-science/community-structure] At the end, the network reaches a point where it is essentially random.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This kind of benchmark may be called "open".
[src:network-science/community-structure] The performance on these benchmarks is evaluated by measures such as normalized mutual information or variation of information.
[src:network-science/community-structure] They compare the solution obtained by an algorithm with the original community structure, evaluating the similarity of both partitions.
[src:network-science/community-structure] This transition is independent of the type of algorithm being used to detect communities, implying that there exists a fundamental limit on our ability to detect communities in networks, even with optimal Bayesian inference (i.e., regardless of our computational resources).
[src:network-science/community-structure] Consider a stochastic block model with total n nodes, $q=2$ groups of equal size, and let $p_{\text{in}}$ and $p_{\text{out}}$ be the connection probabilities inside and between the groups respectively.
[src:network-science/community-structure] If $p_{\text{in}}>p_{\text{out}}$ , the network would possess community structure since the link density inside the groups would be more than the density of links between the groups.
[src:network-science/complex-network] In the context of network theory, a **complex network** is a graph (network) with non-trivial topological features—features that do not occur in simple networks such as lattices or random graphs but often occur in networks representing real systems.
[src:network-science/complex-network] The study of complex networks is a young and active area of scientific research (since 2000) inspired largely by empirical findings of real-world networks such as computer networks, biological networks, technological networks, brain networks, and social networks.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Most social, biological, and technological networks display substantial non-trivial topological features, with patterns of connection between their elements that are neither purely regular nor purely random.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Such features include a heavy tail in the degree distribution, a high clustering coefficient, assortativity or disassortativity among vertices, community structure, and hierarchical structure.
[src:network-science/complex-network] In the case of directed networks these features also include reciprocity, triad significance profile and other features.
[src:network-science/complex-network] In contrast, many of the mathematical models of networks that have been studied in the past, such as lattices and random graphs, do not show these features.
[src:network-science/complex-network] The most complex structures can be realized by networks with a medium number of interactions.
[src:network-science/complex-network] This corresponds to the fact that the maximum information content (entropy) is obtained for medium probabilities.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Two well-known and much studied classes of complex networks are scale-free networks and small-world networks, whose discovery and definition are canonical case-studies in the field.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Both are characterized by specific structural features—power-law degree distributions for the former and short path lengths and high clustering for the latter.
[src:network-science/complex-network] However, as the study of complex networks has continued to grow in importance and popularity, many other aspects of network structures have attracted attention as well.
[src:network-science/complex-network] The field continues to develop at a brisk pace, and has brought together researchers from many areas including mathematics, physics, electric power systems, biology, climate, computer science, sociology, epidemiology, and others.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Network science is the topic of many conferences in a variety of different fields, and has been the subject of numerous books both for the lay person and for the expert.
[src:network-science/complex-network] A network is called scale-free if its degree distribution, i.e., the probability that a node selected uniformly at random has a certain number of links (degree), follows a mathematical function called a power law.
[src:network-science/complex-network] The power law implies that the degree distribution of these networks has no characteristic scale.
[src:network-science/complex-network] In contrast, networks with a single well-defined scale are somewhat similar to a lattice in that every node has (roughly) the same degree.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Examples of networks with a single scale include the Erdős–Rényi (ER) random graph, random regular graphs, regular lattices, and hypercubes.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Some models of growing networks that produce scale-invariant degree distributions are the Barabási–Albert model and the fitness model.
[src:network-science/complex-network] If there were such a threshold, the network would not be scale-free.
[src:network-science/complex-network] There are many different ways to build a network with a power-law degree distribution.
[src:network-science/complex-network] The Yule process is a canonical generative process for power laws, and has been known since 1925.
[src:network-science/complex-network] However, it is known by many other names due to its frequent reinvention, e.g., The Gibrat principle by Herbert A.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Simon, the Matthew effect, cumulative advantage and, preferential attachment by Barabási and Albert for power-law degree distributions.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Recently, Hyperbolic Geometric Graphs have been suggested as yet another way of constructing scale-free networks.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Some networks with a power-law degree distribution (and specific other types of structure) can be highly resistant to the random deletion of vertices—i.e., the vast majority of vertices remain connected together in a giant component.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Such networks can also be quite sensitive to targeted attacks aimed at fracturing the network quickly.
[src:network-science/complex-network] While random graphs (ER) have an average distance of order log N between nodes, where N is the number of nodes, scale free graph can have a distance of log log N.
[src:network-science/complex-network] A network is called a small-world network by analogy with the small-world phenomenon (popularly known as six degrees of separation).
[src:network-science/complex-network] Watts and Steven Strogatz published the first small-world network model, which through a single parameter smoothly interpolates between a random graph and a lattice.
[src:network-science/complex-network] It is known that a wide variety of abstract graphs exhibit the small-world property, e.g., random graphs and scale-free networks.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Further, real world networks such as the World Wide Web and the metabolic network also exhibit this property.
[src:network-science/complex-network] In the scientific literature on networks, there is some ambiguity associated with the term "small world".
[src:network-science/complex-network] In addition to referring to the size of the diameter of the network, it can also refer to the co-occurrence of a small diameter and a high clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/complex-network] The clustering coefficient is a metric that represents the density of triangles in the network.
[src:network-science/complex-network] For instance, sparse random graphs have a vanishingly small clustering coefficient while real world networks often have a coefficient significantly larger.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Scientists point to this difference as suggesting that edges are correlated in real world networks.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Approaches have been developed to generate network models that exhibit high correlations, while preserving the desired degree distribution and small-world properties.
[src:network-science/complex-network] These approaches can be used to generate analytically solvable toy models for research into these systems.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Many real networks are embedded in space.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Examples include, transportation and other infrastructure networks, brain networks.
[src:network-science/complex-network] Several models for spatial networks have been developed.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] In the mathematical field of graph theory, the **Erdős–Rényi model**s are two closely related models for generating random graphs and the evolution of a random network.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] These models are named after Hungarian mathematicians Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi, who introduced one of the models in 1959.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Edgar Gilbert introduced the other model contemporaneously with and independently of Erdős and Rényi.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] In the model of Erdős and Rényi, all graphs on a fixed vertex set with a fixed number of edges are equally likely.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] In the model introduced by Gilbert, also called the **Erdős–Rényi–Gilbert model**, each edge has a fixed probability of being present or absent, independently of the other edges.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] These models can be used in the probabilistic method to prove the existence of graphs satisfying various properties, or to provide a rigorous definition of what it means for a property to hold for almost all graphs.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] There are two closely related variants of the Erdős–Rényi random graph model.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] The behavior of random graphs are often studied in the case where n , the number of vertices, tends to infinity.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Although p and M can be fixed in this case, they can also be functions depending on n .
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] For example, the statement that almost every graph in $G(n,2\ln(n)/n)$ is connected means that, as n tends to infinity, the probability that a graph on n vertices with edge probability $2\ln(n)/n$ is connected tends to 1 .
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] The expected number of edges in *G*(*n*, *p*) is ${\tbinom {n}{2}}p$ , with a standard deviation asymptotic to $s(n)=n{\sqrt {p(1-p)}}$ .
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Therefore, a rough heuristic is that if some property of *G*(*n*, *M*) with $M={\tbinom {n}{2}}p$ does not significantly change in behavior if *M* is changed by up to *s*(*n*), then *G*(*n*, *p*) should share that behavior.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] This is formalized in a result of Łuczak.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Suppose that *P* is a graph property such that for every sequence *M* = *M*(*n*) with $|M-{\tbinom {n}{2}}p|=O(s(n))$ , the probability that a graph sampled from *G*(*n*, *M*) has property *P* tends to *a* as *n* → ∞.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Then the probability that *G*(*n*, *p*) has property *P* also tends to *a*.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Implications in the other direction are less reliable, but a partial converse (also shown by Łuczak) is known when *P* is monotone with respect to the subgraph ordering (meaning that if *A* is a subgraph of *B* and *B* satisfies *P*, then *A* will satisfy *P* as well).
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Let $\varepsilon (n)\gg s(n)/n^{3}$ , and suppose that a monotone property *P* is true of both *G*(*n*, *p* – *ε*) and *G*(*n*, *p* + *ε*) with a probability tending to the same constant *a* as *n* → ∞.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Then the probability that $G(n,{\tbinom {n}{2}}p)$ has property *P* also tends to *a*.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] For example, both directions of equivalency hold if *P* is the property of being connected, or if *P* is the property of containing a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] However, properties that are not monotone (e.g. the property of having an even number of edges) or that change too rapidly (e.g. the property of having at least ${\tfrac {1}{2}}{\tbinom {n}{2}}$ edges) may behave differently in the two models.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] In practice, the *G*(*n*, *p*) model is the one more commonly used today, in part due to the ease of analysis allowed by the independence of the edges.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] With the notation above, a graph in *G*(*n*, *p*) has on average ${\tbinom {n}{2}}p$ edges.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] where *n* is the total number of vertices in the graph.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] this distribution is Poisson for large *n* and *np* = const.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] In a 1960 paper, Erdős and Rényi described the behavior of *G*(*n*, *p*) very precisely for various values of *p*.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Thus ${\tfrac {\ln n}{n}}$ is a sharp threshold for the connectedness of *G*(*n*, *p*).
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Further properties of the graph can be described almost precisely as *n* tends to infinity.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] For example, there is a *k*(*n*) (approximately equal to 2log2(*n*)) such that the largest clique in *G*(*n*, 0.5) has almost surely either size *k*(*n*) or *k*(*n*) + 1.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Thus, even though finding the size of the largest clique in a graph is NP-complete, the size of the largest clique in a "typical" graph (according to this model) is very well understood.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Edge-dual graphs of Erdos-Renyi graphs are graphs with nearly the same degree distribution, but with degree correlations and a significantly higher clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] In percolation theory one examines a finite or infinite graph and removes edges (or links) randomly.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Thus the Erdős–Rényi process is in fact unweighted link percolation on the complete graph.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] (One refers to percolation in which nodes and/or links are removed with heterogeneous weights as weighted percolation).
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] As percolation theory has much of its roots in physics, much of the research done was on the lattices in Euclidean spaces.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] The transition at *np* = 1 from giant component to small component has analogs for these graphs, but for lattices the transition point is difficult to determine.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Physicists often refer to study of the complete graph as a mean field theory.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Thus the Erdős–Rényi process is the mean-field case of percolation.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Some significant work was also done on percolation on random graphs.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] From a physicist's point of view this would still be a mean-field model, so the justification of the research is often formulated in terms of the robustness of the graph, viewed as a communication network.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Given a random graph of *n* ≫ 1 nodes with an average degree $\langle k\rangle$ .
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Remove randomly a fraction $1-p'$ of nodes and leave only a fraction $p'$ from the network.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] There exists a critical percolation threshold $p'_{c}={\tfrac {1}{\langle k\rangle }}$ below which the network becomes fragmented while above $p'_{c}$ a giant connected component of order *n* exists.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Both of the two major assumptions of the *G*(*n*, *p*) model (that edges are independent and that each edge is equally likely) may be inappropriate for modeling certain real-life phenomena.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Erdős–Rényi graphs have low clustering, unlike many social networks.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Some modeling alternatives include Barabási–Albert model and Watts and Strogatz model.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] These alternative models are not percolation processes, but instead represent a growth and rewiring model, respectively.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Another alternative family of random graph models, capable of reproducing many real-life phenomena, are exponential random graph models.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] The *G*(*n*, *p*) model was first introduced by Edgar Gilbert in a 1959 paper studying the connectivity threshold mentioned above.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] The *G*(*n*, *M*) model was introduced by Erdős and Rényi in their 1959 paper.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] As with Gilbert, their first investigations were as to the connectivity of *G*(*n*, *M*), with the more detailed analysis following in 1960.
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] A continuum limit of the graph was obtained when p is of order $1/n$ .
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] Applying this procedure, one obtains a sequence of random infinite graphs of decreasing sizes: $(\Gamma _{i})_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:network-science/erdős-rényi-model] The theorem states that this graph corresponds in a certain sense to the limit object of $G_{n}$ as $n\to +\infty$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] The study of networks has emerged in diverse disciplines as a means of analyzing complex relational data.
[src:network-science/network-science] The earliest known paper in this field is the famous Seven Bridges of Königsberg written by Leonhard Euler in 1736.
[src:network-science/network-science] Euler's mathematical description of vertices and edges was the foundation of graph theory, a branch of mathematics that studies the properties of pairwise relations in a network structure.
[src:network-science/network-science] The field of graph theory continued to develop and found applications in chemistry.
[src:network-science/network-science] Dénes Kőnig, a Hungarian mathematician and professor, wrote the first book in Graph Theory, entitled "Theory of finite and infinite graphs", in 1936.
[src:network-science/network-science] In the 1930s Jacob Moreno, a psychologist in the Gestalt tradition, arrived in the United States.
[src:network-science/network-science] He developed the sociogram and presented it to the public in April 1933 at a convention of medical scholars.
[src:network-science/network-science] Moreno claimed that "before the advent of sociometry no one knew what the interpersonal structure of a group 'precisely' looked like".
[src:network-science/network-science] The sociogram was a representation of the social structure of a group of elementary school students.
[src:network-science/network-science] The boys were friends of boys and the girls were friends of girls with the exception of one boy who said he liked a single girl.
[src:network-science/network-science] This network representation of social structure was found so intriguing that it was printed in The New York Times.
[src:network-science/network-science] The sociogram has found many applications and has grown into the field of social network analysis.
[src:network-science/network-science] Probabilistic theory in network science developed as an offshoot of graph theory with Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi's eight famous papers on random graphs.
[src:network-science/network-science] For social networks the exponential random graph model or p* is a notational framework used to represent the probability space of a tie occurring in a social network.
[src:network-science/network-science] An alternate approach to network probability structures is the network probability matrix, which models the probability of edges occurring in a network, based on the historic presence or absence of the edge in a sample of networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] Interest in networks exploded around 2000, following new discoveries that offered novel mathematical framework to describe different network topologies, leading to the term 'network science'.
[src:network-science/network-science] Albert-László Barabási and Reka Albert discovered the scale-free networks nature of many real networks, from the WWW to the cell.
[src:network-science/network-science] The scale-free property captures the fact that in real network hubs coexist with many small degree vertices, and the authors offered a dynamical model to explain the origin of this scale-free state.
[src:network-science/network-science] Social networks in particular tend to be weakly scale-free.
[src:network-science/network-science] Duncan Watts and Steven Strogatz reconciled empirical data on networks with mathematical representation, describing the small-world network.
[src:network-science/network-science] The definition of deterministic network is defined compared with the definition of probabilistic network.
[src:network-science/network-science] In un-weighted deterministic networks, edges either exist or not, usually we use 0 to represent non-existence of an edge while 1 to represent existence of an edge.
[src:network-science/network-science] In weighted deterministic networks, the edge value represents the weight of each edge, for example, the strength level.
[src:network-science/network-science] In probabilistic networks, values behind each edge represent the likelihood of the existence of each edge.
[src:network-science/network-science] For example, if one edge has a value equals to 0.9, we say the existence probability of this edge is 0.9.
[src:network-science/network-science] Often, networks have certain attributes that can be calculated to analyze the properties & characteristics of the network.
[src:network-science/network-science] The behavior of these network properties often define network models and can be used to analyze how certain models contrast to each other.
[src:network-science/network-science] Many of the definitions for other terms used in network science can be found in Glossary of graph theory.
[src:network-science/network-science] The size of a network can refer to the number of nodes N or, less commonly, the number of edges E which (for connected graphs with no multi-edges) can range from $N-1$ (a tree) to $E_{\max }$ (a complete graph).
[src:network-science/network-science] In the circumstance of a graph within which multiple edges may exist between a pair of vertices, $E_{\max }=\infty$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] The density D of a network is defined as a normalized ratio between 0 and 1 of the number of edges E to the number of possible edges in a network with N nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] Another possible equation is $D={\frac {T-2N+2}{N(N-3)+2}},$ whereas the ties T are unidirectional (Wasserman & Faust 1994).
[src:network-science/network-science] This gives a better overview over the network density, because unidirectional relationships can be measured.
[src:network-science/network-science] The degree k of a node is the number of edges connected to it.
[src:network-science/network-science] In the ER random graph model ( $G(N,p)$ ) we can compute the expected value of $\langle k\rangle$ (equal to the expected value of k of an arbitrary vertex): a random vertex has $N-1$ other vertices in the network available, and with probability p , connects to each.
[src:network-science/network-science] The degree distribution $P(k)$ is a fundamental property of both real networks, such as the Internet and social networks, and of theoretical models.
[src:network-science/network-science] The degree distribution *P*(*k*) of a network is defined to be the fraction of nodes in the network with degree *k*.
[src:network-science/network-science] The simplest network model, for example, the (Erdős–Rényi model) random graph, in which each of *n* nodes is independently connected (or not) with probability *p* (or 1 − *p*), has a binomial distribution of degrees *k* (or Poisson in the limit of large *n*).
[src:network-science/network-science] Most real networks, from the WWW to protein interaction networks, however, have a degree distribution that are highly right-skewed, meaning that a large majority of nodes have low degree but a small number, known as "hubs", have high degree.
[src:network-science/network-science] For such scale-free networks the degree distribution approximately follows a power law: $P(k)\sim k^{-\gamma }$ , where *γ* is the degree exponent, and is a constant.
[src:network-science/network-science] Such scale-free networks have unexpected structural and dynamical properties, rooted in the diverging second moment of the degree distribution.
[src:network-science/network-science] This shows us, on average, the number of steps it takes to get from one member of the network to another.
[src:network-science/network-science] For faster-than-logarithmic growth, the model does not produce small worlds.
[src:network-science/network-science] The special case of $O(\ln \ln N)$ is known as ultra-small world effect.
[src:network-science/network-science] As another means of measuring network graphs, we can define the diameter of a network as the longest of all the calculated shortest paths in a network.
[src:network-science/network-science] It is the shortest distance between the two most distant nodes in the network.
[src:network-science/network-science] In other words, once the shortest path length from every node to all other nodes is calculated, the diameter is the longest of all the calculated path lengths.
[src:network-science/network-science] The diameter is representative of the linear size of a network.
[src:network-science/network-science] If node A-B-C-D are connected, going from A->D this would be the diameter of 3 (3-hops, 3-links).
[src:network-science/network-science] The clustering coefficient is a measure of an "all-my-friends-know-each-other" property.
[src:network-science/network-science] This is sometimes described as the friends of my friends are my friends.
[src:network-science/network-science] More precisely, the clustering coefficient of a node is the ratio of existing links connecting a node's neighbors to each other to the maximum possible number of such links.
[src:network-science/network-science] The clustering coefficient for the entire network is the average of the clustering coefficients of all the nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] A high clustering coefficient for a network is another indication of a small world.
[src:network-science/network-science] where $k_{i}$ is the number of neighbours of the i 'th node, and $e_{i}$ is the number of connections between these neighbours.
[src:network-science/network-science] From a probabilistic standpoint, the expected local clustering coefficient is the likelihood of a link existing between two arbitrary neighbors of the same node.
[src:network-science/network-science] The way in which a network is connected plays a large part into how networks are analyzed and interpreted.
[src:network-science/network-science] Centrality indices produce rankings which seek to identify the most important nodes in a network model.
[src:network-science/network-science] Different centrality indices encode different contexts for the word "importance." The betweenness centrality, for example, considers a node highly important if it form bridges between many other nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] The eigenvalue centrality, in contrast, considers a node highly important if many other highly important nodes link to it.
[src:network-science/network-science] Hundreds of such measures have been proposed in the literature.
[src:network-science/network-science] Centrality indices are only accurate for identifying the most important nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] The measures are seldom, if ever, meaningful for the remainder of network nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] Also, their indications are only accurate within their assumed context for importance, and tend to "get it wrong" for other contexts.
[src:network-science/network-science] For example, imagine two separate communities whose only link is an edge between the most junior member of each community.
[src:network-science/network-science] Since any transfer from one community to the other must go over this link, the two junior members will have high betweenness centrality.
[src:network-science/network-science] But, since they are junior, (presumably) they have few connections to the "important" nodes in their community, meaning their eigenvalue centrality would be quite low.
[src:network-science/network-science] Limitations to centrality measures have led to the development of more general measures.
[src:network-science/network-science] Two examples are the **accessibility**, which uses the diversity of random walks to measure how accessible the rest of the network is from a given start node, and the **expected force**, derived from the expected value of the force of infection generated by a node.
[src:network-science/network-science] Both of these measures can be meaningfully computed from the structure of the network alone.
[src:network-science/network-science] Nodes in a network may be partitioned into groups representing communities.
[src:network-science/network-science] Depending on the context, communities may be distinct or overlapping.
[src:network-science/network-science] Typically, nodes in such communities will be strongly connected to other nodes in the same community, but weakly connected to nodes outside the community.
[src:network-science/network-science] In the absence of a ground truth describing the community structure of a specific network, several algorithms have been developed to infer possible community structures using either supervised of unsupervised clustering methods.
[src:network-science/network-science] Network models serve as a foundation to understanding interactions within empirical complex networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] Various random graph generation models produce network structures that may be used in comparison to real-world complex networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] The Erdős–Rényi model, named for Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi, is used for generating random graphs in which edges are set between nodes with equal probabilities.
[src:network-science/network-science] It can be used in the probabilistic method to prove the existence of graphs satisfying various properties, or to provide a rigorous definition of what it means for a property to hold for almost all graphs.
[src:network-science/network-science] To generate an Erdős–Rényi model $G(n,p)$ two parameters must be specified: the total number of nodes n and the probability p that a random pair of nodes has an edge.
[src:network-science/network-science] In this model the clustering coefficient is 0 a.s.
[src:network-science/network-science] The behavior of $G(n,p)$ can be broken into three regions.
[src:network-science/network-science] The largest connected component has high complexity.
[src:network-science/network-science] All other components are simple and small $|C_{2}|=O(\log n)$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] The configuration model takes a degree sequence or degree distribution (which subsequently is used to generate a degree sequence) as the input, and produces randomly connected graphs in all respects other than the degree sequence.
[src:network-science/network-science] This means that for a given choice of the degree sequence, the graph is chosen uniformly at random from the set of all graphs that comply with this degree sequence.
[src:network-science/network-science] The degree k of a randomly chosen vertex is an independent and identically distributed random variable with integer values.
[src:network-science/network-science] When ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} [k^{2}]-2\mathbb {E} [k]>0}$ , the configuration graph contains the giant connected component, which has infinite size.
[src:network-science/network-science] The rest of the components have finite sizes, which can be quantified with the notion of the size distribution.
[src:network-science/network-science] The giant component can be destroyed by randomly removing the critical fraction $p_{c}$ of all edges.
[src:network-science/network-science] This process is called percolation on random networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] In the directed configuration model, the degree of a node is given by two numbers, in-degree $k_{\text{in}}$ and out-degree $k_{\text{out}}$ , and consequently, the degree distribution is two-variate.
[src:network-science/network-science] The expected number of in-edges and out-edges coincides, so that ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} [k_{\text{in}}]=\mathbb {E} [k_{\text{out}}]}$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] The Watts and Strogatz model is a random graph generation model that produces graphs with small-world properties.
[src:network-science/network-science] An initial lattice structure is used to generate a Watts–Strogatz model.
[src:network-science/network-science] Each node in the network is initially linked to its $\langle k\rangle$ closest neighbors.
[src:network-science/network-science] Another parameter is specified as the rewiring probability.
[src:network-science/network-science] Each edge has a probability p that it will be rewired to the graph as a random edge.
[src:network-science/network-science] The expected number of rewired links in the model is $pE=pN\langle k\rangle /2$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] As the Watts–Strogatz model begins as a non-random lattice structure, it has a very high clustering coefficient along with a high average path length.
[src:network-science/network-science] Each rewire is likely to create a shortcut between highly connected clusters.
[src:network-science/network-science] As the rewiring probability increases, the clustering coefficient decreases slower than the average path length.
[src:network-science/network-science] In effect, this allows the average path length of the network to decrease significantly with only slight decreases in the clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/network-science] Higher values of p force more rewired edges, which, in effect, makes the Watts–Strogatz model a random network.
[src:network-science/network-science] The Barabási–Albert model is a random network model used to demonstrate a preferential attachment or a "rich-get-richer" effect.
[src:network-science/network-science] In this model, an edge is most likely to attach to nodes with higher degrees.
[src:network-science/network-science] The network begins with an initial network of *m*0 nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] *m*0 ≥ 2 and the degree of each node in the initial network should be at least 1, otherwise it will always remain disconnected from the rest of the network.
[src:network-science/network-science] In the BA model, new nodes are added to the network one at a time.
[src:network-science/network-science] Each new node is connected to m existing nodes with a probability that is proportional to the number of links that the existing nodes already have.
[src:network-science/network-science] Hubs exhibit high betweenness centrality which allows short paths to exist between nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] As a result, the BA model tends to have very short average path lengths.
[src:network-science/network-science] The clustering coefficient of this model also tends to 0.
[src:network-science/network-science] The Barabási–Albert model was developed for undirected networks, aiming to explain the universality of the scale-free property, and applied to a wide range of different networks and applications.
[src:network-science/network-science] The directed version of this model is the Price model which was developed to just citation networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] In non-linear preferential attachment (NLPA), existing nodes in the network gain new edges proportionally to the node degree raised to a constant positive power, $\alpha$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] Another model where the key ingredient is the nature of the vertex has been introduced by Caldarelli et al.
[src:network-science/network-science] Here a link is created between two vertices $i,j$ with a probability given by a linking function $f(\eta _{i},\eta _{j})$ of the fitnesses of the vertices involved.
[src:network-science/network-science] As a result, if the fitnesses $\eta$ are distributed as a power law, then also the node degree does.
[src:network-science/network-science] with Z a constant and $\Theta$ the Heavyside function, we also obtain scale-free networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] Exponential family random graph models (ERGMs) are a family of statistical models for analyzing data from social and other networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] The Exponential family is a broad family of models for covering many types of data, not just networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] An ERGM is a model from this family which describes networks.
[src:network-science/network-science] We adopt the notation to represent a random graph $Y\in {\mathcal {Y}}$ via a set of n nodes and a collection of tie variables $\{Y_{ij}:i=1,\dots ,n;j=1,\dots ,n\}$ , indexed by pairs of nodes $ij$ , where $Y_{ij}=1$ if the nodes $(i,j)$ are connected by an edge and $Y_{ij}=0$ otherwise.
[src:network-science/network-science] The basic assumption of ERGMs is that the structure in an observed graph y can be explained by a given vector of sufficient statistics $s(y)$ which are a function of the observed network and, in some cases, nodal attributes.
[src:network-science/network-science] where $\theta$ is a vector of model parameters associated with $s(y)$ and $c(\theta )=\sum _{y'\in {\mathcal {Y}}}\exp(\theta ^{T}s(y'))$ is a normalising constant.
[src:network-science/network-science] Social network analysis examines the structure of relationships between social entities.
[src:network-science/network-science] These entities are often persons, but may also be groups, organizations, nation states, web sites, scholarly publications.
[src:network-science/network-science] Since the 1970s, the empirical study of networks has played a central role in social science, and many of the mathematical and statistical tools used for studying networks have been first developed in sociology.
[src:network-science/network-science] Amongst many other applications, social network analysis has been used to understand the diffusion of innovation, news and rumors.
[src:network-science/network-science] Similarly, it has been used to examine the spread of both diseases and health-related behaviors.
[src:network-science/network-science] It has also been applied to the study of markets, where it has been used to examine the role of trust in exchange relationships and of social mechanisms in setting prices.
[src:network-science/network-science] Similarly, it has been used to study recruitment into political movements and social organizations.
[src:network-science/network-science] It has also been used to conceptualize scientific disagreements as well as academic prestige.
[src:network-science/network-science] More recently, network analysis (and its close cousin traffic analysis) has gained a significant use in military intelligence, for uncovering insurgent networks of both hierarchical and leaderless nature.
[src:network-science/network-science] In criminology, it is being used to identify influential actors in criminal gangs, offender movements, co-offending, predict criminal activities and make policies.
[src:network-science/network-science] Dynamic network analysis examines the shifting structure of relationships among different classes of entities in complex socio-technical systems effects, and reflects social stability and changes such as the emergence of new groups, topics, and leaders.
[src:network-science/network-science] Dynamic network analysis focuses on meta-networks composed of multiple types of nodes (entities) and multiple types of links.
[src:network-science/network-science] Examples include people, organizations, topics, resources, tasks, events, locations, and beliefs.
[src:network-science/network-science] Dynamic network techniques are particularly useful for assessing trends and changes in networks over time, identification of emergent leaders, and examining the co-evolution of people and ideas.
[src:network-science/network-science] With the recent explosion of publicly available high throughput biological data, the analysis of molecular networks has gained significant interest.
[src:network-science/network-science] The type of analysis in this content are closely related to social network analysis, but often focusing on local patterns in the network.
[src:network-science/network-science] For example, network motifs are small subgraphs that are over-represented in the network.
[src:network-science/network-science] Activity motifs are similar over-represented patterns in the attributes of nodes and edges in the network that are over represented given the network structure.
[src:network-science/network-science] The analysis of biological networks has led to the development of network medicine, which looks at the effect of diseases in the interactome.
[src:network-science/network-science] Semantic network analysis is a sub-field of network analysis that focuses on the relationships between words and concepts in a network.
[src:network-science/network-science] Words are represented as nodes and their proximity or co-occurrences in the text are represented as edges.
[src:network-science/network-science] Semantic networks are therefore graphical representations of knowledge and are commonly used in neurolinguistics and natural language processing applications.
[src:network-science/network-science] Semantic network analysis is also used as a method to analyze large texts and identify the main themes and topics (e.g., of social media posts), to reveal biases (e.g., in news coverage), or even to map an entire research field.
[src:network-science/network-science] Link analysis is a subset of network analysis, exploring associations between objects.
[src:network-science/network-science] An example may be examining the addresses of suspects and victims, the telephone numbers they have dialed, financial transactions they have partaken in during a given timeframe, and the familial relationships between these subjects as a part of the police investigation.
[src:network-science/network-science] Link analysis here provides the crucial relationships and associations between objects of different types that are not apparent from isolated pieces of information.
[src:network-science/network-science] The SIR model is one of the most well known algorithms on predicting the spread of global pandemics within an infectious population.
[src:network-science/network-science] The formula above describes the "force" of infection for each susceptible unit in an infectious population, where β is equivalent to the transmission rate of said disease.
[src:network-science/network-science] Over time, the number of those infected fluctuates by: the specified rate of recovery, represented by $\mu$ but deducted to one over the average infectious period ${1 \over \tau }$ , the numbered of infectious individuals, I , and the change in time, $\Delta t$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] Several Web search ranking algorithms use link-based centrality metrics, including (in order of appearance) Marchiori's Hyper Search, Google's PageRank, Kleinberg's HITS algorithm, the CheiRank and TrustRank algorithms.
[src:network-science/network-science] Link analysis is also conducted in information science and communication science in order to understand and extract information from the structure of collections of web pages.
[src:network-science/network-science] For example, the analysis might be of the interlinking between politicians' web sites or blogs.
[src:network-science/network-science] PageRank works by randomly picking "nodes" or websites and then with a certain probability, "randomly jumping" to other nodes.
[src:network-science/network-science] By randomly jumping to these other nodes, it helps PageRank completely traverse the network as some webpages exist on the periphery and would not as readily be assessed.
[src:network-science/network-science] Each node, $x_{i}$ , has a PageRank as defined by the sum of pages j that link to i times one over the outlinks or "out-degree" of j times the "importance" or PageRank of j .
[src:network-science/network-science] As explained above, PageRank enlists random jumps in attempts to assign PageRank to every website on the internet.
[src:network-science/network-science] These random jumps find websites that might not be found during the normal search methodologies such as breadth-first search and depth-first search.
[src:network-science/network-science] In an improvement over the aforementioned formula for determining PageRank includes adding these random jump components.
[src:network-science/network-science] Without the random jumps, some pages would receive a PageRank of 0 which would not be good.
[src:network-science/network-science] The first is $\alpha$ , or the probability that a random jump will occur.
[src:network-science/network-science] Contrasting is the "damping factor", or $1-\alpha$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] Information about the relative importance of nodes and edges in a graph can be obtained through centrality measures, widely used in disciplines like sociology.
[src:network-science/network-science] Formally established measures of centrality are degree centrality, closeness centrality, betweenness centrality, eigenvector centrality, and katz centrality.
[src:network-science/network-science] The objective of network analysis generally determines the type of centrality measure(s) to be used.
[src:network-science/network-science] Content in a complex network can spread via two major methods: conserved spread and non-conserved spread.
[src:network-science/network-science] In conserved spread, the total amount of content that enters a complex network remains constant as it passes through.
[src:network-science/network-science] The model of conserved spread can best be represented by a pitcher containing a fixed amount of water being poured into a series of funnels connected by tubes.
[src:network-science/network-science] The pitcher represents the source, and the water represents the spread content.
[src:network-science/network-science] The funnels and connecting tubing represent the nodes and the connections between nodes, respectively.
[src:network-science/network-science] As the water passes from one funnel into another, the water disappears instantly from the funnel that was previously exposed to the water.
[src:network-science/network-science] In non-conserved spread, the content changes as it enters and passes through a complex network.
[src:network-science/network-science] The model of non-conserved spread can best be represented by a continuously running faucet running through a series of funnels connected by tubes.
[src:network-science/network-science] Here, the amount of water from the source is infinite.
[src:network-science/network-science] Also, any funnels exposed to the water continue to experience the water even as it passes into successive funnels.
[src:network-science/network-science] The non-conserved model is the most suitable for explaining the transmission of most infectious diseases.
[src:network-science/network-science] McKendrick created a model in which they considered a fixed population with only three compartments, susceptible: $S(t)$ , infected, $I(t)$ , and recovered, $R(t)$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] Therefore, an infected individual makes contact and is able to transmit the disease with $\beta N$ others per unit time and the fraction of contacts by an infected with a susceptible is $S/N$ .
[src:network-science/network-science] The number of new infections in unit time per infective then is $\beta N(S/N)$ , giving the rate of new infections (or those leaving the susceptible category) as $\beta N(S/N)I=\beta SI$ (Brauer & Castillo-Chavez, 2001).
[src:network-science/network-science] For the second and third equations, consider the population leaving the susceptible class as equal to the number entering the infected class.
[src:network-science/network-science] However, infectives are leaving this class per unit time to enter the recovered/removed class at a rate $\gamma$ per unit time (where $\gamma$ represents the mean recovery rate, or $1/\gamma$ the mean infective period).
[src:network-science/network-science] These processes which occur simultaneously are referred to as the Law of Mass Action, a widely accepted idea that the rate of contact between two groups in a population is proportional to the size of each of the groups concerned (Daley & Gani, 2005).
[src:network-science/network-science] Finally, it is assumed that the rate of infection and recovery is much faster than the time scale of births and deaths and therefore, these factors are ignored in this model.
[src:network-science/network-science] More can be read on this model on the Epidemic model page.
[src:network-science/network-science] A master equation can express the behaviour of an undirected growing network where, at each time step, a new node is added to the network, linked to an old node (randomly chosen and without preference).
[src:network-science/network-science] The initial network is formed by two nodes and two links between them at time $t=2$ , this configuration is necessary only to simplify further calculations, so at time $t=n$ the network have n nodes and n links.
[src:network-science/network-science] where $p(k,s,t)$ is the probability to have the node s with degree k at time $t+1$ , and s is the time step when this node was added to the network.
[src:network-science/network-science] Based on this growing network, an epidemic model is developed following a simple rule: Each time the new node is added and after choosing the old node to link, a decision is made: whether or not this new node will be infected.
[src:network-science/network-science] Multilayer networks are networks with multiple kinds of relations.
[src:network-science/network-science] Network problems that involve finding an optimal way of doing something are studied under the name of combinatorial optimization.
[src:network-science/network-science] Examples include network flow, shortest path problem, transport problem, transshipment problem, location problem, matching problem, assignment problem, packing problem, routing problem, critical path analysis and PERT (program evaluation and review technique).
[src:network-science/network-science] Interdependent networks are networks where the functioning of nodes in one network depends on the functioning of nodes in another network.
[src:network-science/network-science] In nature, networks rarely appear in isolation, rather, usually networks are typically elements in larger systems, and interact with elements in that complex system.
[src:network-science/network-science] Such complex dependencies can have non-trivial effects on one another.
[src:network-science/network-science] A well studied example is the interdependency of infrastructure networks, the power stations which form the nodes of the power grid require fuel delivered via a network of roads or pipes and are also controlled via the nodes of communications network.
[src:network-science/network-science] Though the transportation network does not depend on the power network to function, the communications network does.
[src:network-science/network-science] In such infrastructure networks, the disfunction of a critical number of nodes in either the power network or the communication network can lead to cascading failures across the system with potentially catastrophic result to the whole system functioning.
[src:network-science/network-science] If the two networks were treated in isolation, this important feedback effect would not be seen and predictions of network robustness would be greatly overestimated.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] A **scale-free network** is a network whose degree distribution follows a power law, at least asymptotically.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] where $\gamma$ is a parameter whose value is typically in the range ${\textstyle 2<\gamma <3}$ (wherein the second moment (scale parameter) of $k^{\boldsymbol {-\gamma }}$ is infinite but the first moment is finite), although occasionally it may lie outside these bounds.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The name "scale-free" could be explained by the fact that some moments of the degree distribution are not defined, so that the network does not have a characteristic scale or "size".
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Preferential attachment and the fitness model have been proposed as mechanisms to explain the power law degree distributions in real networks.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Alternative models such as super-linear preferential attachment and second-neighbour preferential attachment may appear to generate transient scale-free networks, but the degree distribution deviates from a power law as networks become very large.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In studies of citations between scientific papers, Derek de Solla Price showed in 1965 that the number of citations a paper receives had a heavy-tailed distribution following a Pareto distribution or power law.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In a later paper in 1976, Price also proposed a mechanism to explain the occurrence of power laws in citation networks, which he called "cumulative advantage." However, both treated citations are scalar quantities, rather than a fundamental feature of a new class of networks.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In a subsequent paper Barabási and Albert showed that the power laws are not a unique property of the WWW, but the feature is present in a few real networks, prompting them to coin the term "scale-free network" to describe the class of networks that exhibit a power-law degree distribution.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Barabási and Réka Albert proposed a generative mechanism to explain the appearance of power-law distributions, which they called "preferential attachment".
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Analytic solutions for this mechanism were presented in 2000 by Dorogovtsev, Mendes and Samukhin and independently by Krapivsky, Redner, and Leyvraz, and later rigorously proved by mathematician Béla Bollobás.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] When the concept of "scale-free" was initially introduced in the context of networks, it primarily referred to a specific trait: a power-law distribution for a given variable k , expressed as $f(k)\propto k^{-\gamma }$ .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This property maintains its form when subjected to a continuous scale transformation $k\to k+\epsilon k$ , evoking parallels with the renormalization group techniques in statistical field theory.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In statistical field theory, the term "scale" often pertains to system size.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In the realm of networks, "scale" k is a measure of connectivity, generally quantified by a node's degree—that is, the number of links attached to it.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Networks featuring a higher number of high-degree nodes are deemed to have greater connectivity.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The power-law degree distribution enables us to make "scale-free" assertions about the prevalence of high-degree nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] For instance, we can say that "nodes with triple the average connectivity occur half as frequently as nodes with average connectivity".
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The specific numerical value of what constitutes "average connectivity" becomes irrelevant, whether it's a hundred or a million.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The most notable characteristic in a scale-free network is the relative commonness of vertices with a degree that greatly exceeds the average.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The highest-degree nodes are often called "hubs", and are thought to serve specific purposes in their networks, although this depends greatly on the domain.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In a random network the maximum degree, or the expected largest hub, scales as *kmax~ log N*, where *N* is the network size, a very slow dependence.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In contrast, in scale-free networks the largest hub scales as *kmax~ ~N1/(γ−1)* indicating that the hubs increase polynomically with the size of the network.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] A key feature of scale-free networks is their high degree heterogeneity, κ= *<k2>/<k>*, which governs multiple network-based processes, from network robustness to epidemic spreading and network synchronization.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] While for a random network κ= *<k> + 1,* i.e. the ration is independent of the network size *N*, for a scale-free network we have κ*~ N(3−γ)/(γ−1)*, increasing with the network size, indicating that for these networks the degree heterogeneity increases.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Another important characteristic of scale-free networks is the clustering coefficient distribution, which decreases as the node degree increases.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This distribution also follows a power law.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This implies that the low-degree nodes belong to very dense sub-graphs and those sub-graphs are connected to each other through hubs.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Consider a social network in which nodes are people and links are acquaintance relationships between people.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] It is easy to see that people tend to form communities, i.e., small groups in which everyone knows everyone (one can think of such community as a complete graph).
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In addition, the members of a community also have a few acquaintance relationships to people outside that community.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Some people, however, are connected to a large number of communities (e.g., celebrities, politicians).
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Those people may be considered the hubs responsible for the small-world phenomenon.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] At present, the more specific characteristics of scale-free networks vary with the generative mechanism used to create them.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] For instance, networks generated by preferential attachment typically place the high-degree vertices in the middle of the network, connecting them together to form a core, with progressively lower-degree nodes making up the regions between the core and the periphery.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The random removal of even a large fraction of vertices impacts the overall connectedness of the network very little, suggesting that such topologies could be useful for security, while targeted attacks destroys the connectedness very quickly.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Other scale-free networks, which place the high-degree vertices at the periphery, do not exhibit these properties.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Similarly, the clustering coefficient of scale-free networks can vary significantly depending on other topological details.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The question of how to immunize efficiently scale free networks which represent realistic networks such as the Internet and social networks has been studied extensively.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] One such strategy is to immunize the largest degree nodes, i.e., targeted (intentional) attacks since for this case p c is relatively high and less nodes are needed to be immunized.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] However, in many realistic cases the global structure is not available and the largest degree nodes are not known.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Properties of random graph may change or remain invariant under graph transformations.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Mashaghi A. et al., for example, demonstrated that a transformation which converts random graphs to their edge-dual graphs (or line graphs) produces an ensemble of graphs with nearly the same degree distribution, but with degree correlations and a significantly higher clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Scale free graphs, as such, remain scale free under such transformations.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Scale free topology has been also found in high temperature superconductors.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The qualities of a high-temperature superconductor — a compound in which electrons obey the laws of quantum physics, and flow in perfect synchrony, without friction — appear linked to the fractal arrangements of seemingly random oxygen atoms and lattice distortion.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Scale-free networks do not arise by chance alone.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Erdős and Rényi (1960) studied a model of growth for graphs in which, at each step, two nodes are chosen uniformly at random and a link is inserted between them.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The properties of these random graphs are different from the properties found in scale-free networks, and therefore a model for this growth process is needed.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] According to this process, a page with many in-links will attract more in-links than a regular page.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This generates a power-law but the resulting graph differs from the actual Web graph in other properties such as the presence of small tightly connected communities.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] More general models and network characteristics have been proposed and studied.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] (2018) proposed a variant of the rich get richer generative model which takes into account two different attachment rules: a preferential attachment mechanism and a uniform choice only for the most recent nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] For a review see the book by Dorogovtsev and Mendes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Some mechanisms such as super-linear preferential attachment and second neighbour attachment generate networks which are transiently scale-free, but deviate from a power law as networks grow large.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] A somewhat different generative model for Web links has been suggested by Pennock et al.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] They examined communities with interests in a specific topic such as the home pages of universities, public companies, newspapers or scientists, and discarded the major hubs of the Web.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In this case, the distribution of links was no longer a power law but resembled a normal distribution.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Based on these observations, the authors proposed a generative model that mixes preferential attachment with a baseline probability of gaining a link.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Another generative model is the **copy** model studied by Kumar et al.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] (2000), in which new nodes choose an existent node at random and copy a fraction of the links of the existent node.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] There are two major components that explain the emergence of the power-law distribution in the Barabási–Albert model: the growth and the preferential attachment.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] By "growth" is meant a growth process where, over an extended period of time, new nodes join an already existing system, a network (like the World Wide Web which has grown by billions of web pages over 10 years).
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Finally, by "preferential attachment" is meant that new nodes prefer to connect to nodes that already have a high number of links with others.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Thus, there is a higher probability that more and more nodes will link themselves to that one which has already many links, leading this node to a hub *in-fine*.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Depending on the network, the hubs might either be assortative or disassortative.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Assortativity would be found in social networks in which well-connected/famous people would tend to know better each other.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Disassortativity would be found in technological (Internet, World Wide Web) and biological (protein interaction, metabolism) networks.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] However, the *growth* of the networks (adding new nodes) is not a necessary condition for creating a scale-free network (see Dangalchev).
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] 2002) is to consider the structure as static and draw a link between vertices according to a particular property of the two vertices involved.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Once specified the statistical distribution for these vertex properties (fitnesses), it turns out that in some circumstances also static networks develop scale-free properties.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] There has been a burst of activity in the modeling of scale-free complex networks.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The recipe of Barabási and Albert has been followed by several variations and generalizations and the revamping of previous mathematical works.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In today's terms, if a complex network has a power-law distribution of any of its metrics, it's generally considered a scale-free network.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Similarly, any model with this feature is called a scale-free model.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Many real networks are (approximately) scale-free and hence require scale-free models to describe them.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Preferential attachment: The probability $\Pi$ that new nodes will be connected to the "old" node.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Note that some models (see Dangalchev and Fitness model below) can work also statically, without changing the number of nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] There have been several attempts to generate scale-free network properties.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The Barabási–Albert model, an undirected version of Price's model has a linear preferential attachment $\Pi (k_{i})={\frac {k_{i}}{\sum _{j}k_{j}}}$ and adds one new node at every time step.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] (Note, another general feature of $\Pi (k)$ in real networks is that $\Pi (0)\neq 0$ , i.e. there is a nonzero probability that a new node attaches to an isolated node.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Dangalchev (see ) builds a 2-L model by considering the importance of each of the neighbours of a target node in preferential attachment.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The attractiveness of a node in the 2-L model depends not only on the number of nodes linked to it but also on the number of links in each of these nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] where *C* is a coefficient between 0 and 1.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] A variant of the 2-L model, the k2 model, where first and second neighbour nodes contribute equally to a target node's attractiveness, demonstrates the emergence of transient scale-free networks.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In the k2 model, the degree distribution appears approximately scale-free as long as the network is relatively small, but significant deviations from the scale-free regime emerge as the network grows larger.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This results in the relative attractiveness of nodes with different degrees changing over time, a feature also observed in real networks.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The Barabási–Albert model assumes that the probability $\Pi (k)$ that a node attaches to node i is proportional to the degree k of node i .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This assumption involves two hypotheses: first, that $\Pi (k)$ depends on k , in contrast to random graphs in which $\Pi (k)=p$ , and second, that the functional form of $\Pi (k)$ is linear in k .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Krapivsky, Redner, and Leyvraz demonstrate that the scale-free nature of the network is destroyed for nonlinear preferential attachment.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The only case in which the topology of the network is scale free is that in which the preferential attachment is asymptotically linear, i.e. $\Pi (k_{i})\sim a_{\infty }k_{i}$ as $k_{i}\to \infty$ .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This way the exponent of the degree distribution can be tuned to any value between 2 and $\infty$ .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Hierarchical network models are, by design, scale free and have high clustering of nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The iterative construction leads to a hierarchical network.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Starting from a fully connected cluster of five nodes, we create four identical replicas connecting the peripheral nodes of each cluster to the central node of the original cluster.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] From this, we get a network of 25 nodes (*N* = 25).
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Repeating the same process, we can create four more replicas of the original cluster – the four peripheral nodes of each one connect to the central node of the nodes created in the first step.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This gives *N* = 125, and the process can continue indefinitely.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The idea is that the link between two vertices is assigned not randomly with a probability *p* equal for all the couple of vertices.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Rather, for every vertex *j* there is an intrinsic *fitness* *x**j* and a link between vertex *i* and *j* is created with a probability $p(x_{i},x_{j})$ .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Assuming that a network has an underlying hyperbolic geometry, one can use the framework of spatial networks to generate scale-free degree distributions.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This heterogeneous degree distribution then simply reflects the negative curvature and metric properties of the underlying hyperbolic geometry.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Starting with scale free graphs with low degree correlation and clustering coefficient, one can generate new graphs with much higher degree correlations and clustering coefficients by applying edge-dual transformation.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This modification is interesting to study the robustness of the scale-free behavior of the degree distribution.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] It is proved analytically that the asymptotically power-law degree distribution is preserved.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In the context of network theory a **scale-free ideal network** is a random network with a degree distribution following the scale-free ideal gas density distribution.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] These networks are able to reproduce city-size distributions and electoral results by unraveling the size distribution of social groups with information theory on complex networks when a competitive cluster growth process is applied to the network.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In models of scale-free ideal networks it is possible to demonstrate that Dunbar's number is the cause of the phenomenon known as the 'six degrees of separation'.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] For a scale-free network with n nodes and power-law exponent $\gamma >3$ , the induced subgraph constructed by vertices with degrees larger than $\log {n}\times \log ^{*}{n}$ is a scale-free network with $\gamma '=2$ , almost surely.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] On a theoretical level, refinements to the abstract definition of scale-free have been proposed.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] (2005) offered a potentially more precise "scale-free metric".
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Briefly, let *G* be a graph with edge set *E*, and denote the degree of a vertex v (that is, the number of edges incident to v ) by $\deg(v)$ .
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This is maximized when high-degree nodes are connected to other high-degree nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] where *s*max is the maximum value of *s*(*H*) for *H* in the set of all graphs with degree distribution identical to that of *G*.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This gives a metric between 0 and 1, where a graph *G* with small *S*(*G*) is "scale-rich", and a graph *G* with *S*(*G*) close to 1 is "scale-free".
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] This definition captures the notion of self-similarity implied in the name "scale-free".
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Estimating the power-law exponent $\gamma$ of a scale-free network is typically done by using the maximum likelihood estimation with the degrees of a few uniformly sampled nodes.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] However, since uniform sampling does not obtain enough samples from the important heavy-tail of the power law degree distribution, this method can yield a large bias and a variance.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] It has been recently proposed to sample random friends (i.e., random ends of random links) who are more likely come from the tail of the degree distribution as a result of the friendship paradox.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Theoretically, maximum likelihood estimation with random friends lead to a smaller bias and a smaller variance compared to classical approach based on uniform sampling.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] The widespread property of the scale-free property in social, biological and technological systems does not mean that *all* real networks are scale-free.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Rather, several important networks do not share this property, like networks appearing in material science, describing the bonds between the atoms in crystalline or amorphous materials.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] In these networks each node has the same degree, determined by chemistry.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Also, the neural network of the *C. elegans* worm and the power grid, consisting of generators and switches connected by transmission lines, have been shown to have exponential degree distributions.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] Further, in some real-world network's scale-free quality can be stronger or weaker.
[src:network-science/scale-free-network] For example, social networks tend to be weakly scale-free, while some technological and biological networks can be strongly scale-free.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A **small-world network** is a graph characterized by a high clustering coefficient and low distances.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In an example of a social network, high clustering implies the high probability that two friends of one person are friends themselves.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The low distances, on the other hand, mean that there is a short chain of social connections between any two people (this effect is known as six degrees of separation).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] while the global clustering coefficient is not small.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In the context of a social network, this results in the small world phenomenon of strangers being linked by a short chain of acquaintances.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Many empirical graphs show the small-world effect, including social networks, wikis such as Wikipedia, gene networks, and even the underlying architecture of the Internet.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] It is the inspiration for many network-on-chip architectures in contemporary computer hardware.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A certain category of small-world networks were identified as a class of random graphs by Duncan Watts and Steven Strogatz in 1998.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] They noted that graphs could be classified according to two independent structural features, namely the clustering coefficient, and average node-to-node distance (also known as average shortest path length).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Purely random graphs, built according to the Erdős–Rényi (ER) model, exhibit a small average shortest path length (varying typically as the logarithm of the number of nodes) along with a small clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Watts and Strogatz measured that in fact many real-world networks have a small average shortest path length, but also a clustering coefficient significantly higher than expected by random chance.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Watts and Strogatz then proposed a novel graph model, currently named the Watts and Strogatz model, with (i) a small average shortest path length, and (ii) a large clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The crossover in the Watts–Strogatz model between a "large world" (such as a lattice) and a small world was first described by Barthelemy and Amaral in 1999.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This work was followed by many studies, including exact results (Barrat and Weigt, 1999; Dorogovtsev and Mendes; Barmpoutis and Murray, 2010).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small-world networks tend to contain cliques, and near-cliques, meaning sub-networks which have connections between almost any two nodes within them.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This follows from the defining property of a high clustering coefficient.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Secondly, most pairs of nodes will be connected by at least one short path.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This follows from the defining property that the mean-shortest path length be small.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Several other properties are often associated with small-world networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Typically there is an over-abundance of *hubs* – nodes in the network with a high number of connections (known as high degree nodes).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] These hubs serve as the common connections mediating the short path lengths between other edges.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] By analogy, the small-world network of airline flights has a small mean-path length (i.e. between any two cities you are likely to have to take three or fewer flights) because many flights are routed through hub cities.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This property is often analyzed by considering the fraction of nodes in the network that have a particular number of connections going into them (the degree distribution of the network).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Networks with a greater than expected number of hubs will have a greater fraction of nodes with high degree, and consequently the degree distribution will be enriched at high degree values.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This is known colloquially as a fat-tailed distribution.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Graphs of very different topology qualify as small-world networks as long as they satisfy the two definitional requirements above.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Network small-worldness has been quantified by a small-coefficient, $\sigma$ , calculated by comparing clustering and path length of a given network to an Erdős–Rényi model with same degree on average.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] However, this metric is known to perform poorly because it is heavily influenced by the network's size.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Another method for quantifying network small-worldness utilizes the original definition of the small-world network comparing the clustering of a given network to an equivalent lattice network and its path length to an equivalent random network.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Where the characteristic path length *L* and clustering coefficient *C* are calculated from the network you are testing, *C**ℓ* is the clustering coefficient for an equivalent lattice network and *L**r* is the characteristic path length for an equivalent random network.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Still another method for quantifying small-worldness normalizes both the network's clustering and path length relative to these characteristics in equivalent lattice and random networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Both *ω*′ and SWI range between 0 and 1, and have been shown to capture aspects of small-worldness.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] However, they adopt slightly different conceptions of ideal small-worldness.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] For a given set of constraints (e.g. size, density, degree distribution), there exists a network for which *ω*′ = 1, and thus *ω* aims to capture the extent to which a network with given constraints as small worldly as possible.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In contrast, there may not exist a network for which SWI = 1, thus SWI aims to capture the extent to which a network with given constraints approaches the theoretical small world ideal of a network where *C* ≈ *C**ℓ* and *L* ≈ *L**r*.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small-world properties are found in many real-world phenomena, including websites with navigation menus, food webs, electric power grids, metabolite processing networks, networks of brain neurons, voter networks, telephone call graphs, and airport networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Cultural networks and word co-occurrence networks have also been shown to be small-world networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Networks of connected proteins have small world properties such as power-law obeying degree distributions.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Similarly transcriptional networks, in which the nodes are genes, and they are linked if one gene has an up or down-regulatory genetic influence on the other, have small world network properties.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In another example, the famous theory of "six degrees of separation" between people tacitly presumes that the domain of discourse is the set of people alive at any one time.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The number of degrees of separation between Albert Einstein and Alexander the Great is almost certainly greater than 30 and this network does not have small-world properties.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A similarly constrained network would be the "went to school with" network: if two people went to the same college ten years apart from one another, it is unlikely that they have acquaintances in common amongst the student body.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Similarly, the number of relay stations through which a message must pass was not always small.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In the days when the post was carried by hand or on horseback, the number of times a letter changed hands between its source and destination would have been much greater than it is today.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The number of times a message changed hands in the days of the visual telegraph (circa 1800–1850) was determined by the requirement that two stations be connected by line-of-sight.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Tacit assumptions, if not examined, can cause a bias in the literature on graphs in favor of finding small-world networks (an example of the file drawer effect resulting from the publication bias).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] It is hypothesized by some researchers, such as Albert-László Barabási, that the prevalence of small world networks in biological systems may reflect an evolutionary advantage of such an architecture.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] One possibility is that small-world networks are more robust to perturbations than other network architectures.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] If this were the case, it would provide an advantage to biological systems that are subject to damage by mutation or viral infection.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In a small world network with a degree distribution following a power-law, deletion of a random node rarely causes a dramatic increase in mean-shortest path length (or a dramatic decrease in the clustering coefficient).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This follows from the fact that most shortest paths between nodes flow through hubs, and if a peripheral node is deleted it is unlikely to interfere with passage between other peripheral nodes.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] As the fraction of peripheral nodes in a small world network is much higher than the fraction of hubs, the probability of deleting an important node is very low.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] For example, if the small airport in Sun Valley, Idaho was shut down, it would not increase the average number of flights that other passengers traveling in the United States would have to take to arrive at their respective destinations.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] However, if random deletion of a node hits a hub by chance, the average path length can increase dramatically.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This can be observed annually when northern hub airports, such as Chicago's O'Hare airport, are shut down because of snow; many people have to take additional flights.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] By contrast, in a random network, in which all nodes have roughly the same number of connections, deleting a random node is likely to increase the mean-shortest path length slightly but significantly for almost any node deleted.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In this sense, random networks are vulnerable to random perturbations, whereas small-world networks are robust.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] However, small-world networks are vulnerable to targeted attack of hubs, whereas random networks cannot be targeted for catastrophic failure.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The main mechanism to construct small-world networks is the Watts–Strogatz mechanism.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small-world networks can also be introduced with time-delay, which will not only produce fractals but also chaos under the right conditions, or transition to chaos in dynamics networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Soon after the publication of Watts–Strogatz mechanism, approaches have been developed by Mashaghi and co-workers to generate network models that exhibit high degree correlations, while preserving the desired degree distribution and small-world properties.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] These approaches are based on edge-dual transformation and can be used to generate analytically solvable small-world network models for research into these systems.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Degree–diameter graphs are constructed such that the number of neighbors each vertex in the network has is bounded, while the distance from any given vertex in the network to any other vertex (the diameter of the network) is minimized.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Constructing such small-world networks is done as part of the effort to find graphs of order close to the Moore bound.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Another way to construct a small world network from scratch is given in Barmpoutis *et al.*, where a network with very small average distance and very large average clustering is constructed.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A fast algorithm of constant complexity is given, along with measurements of the robustness of the resulting graphs.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Depending on the application of each network, one can start with one such "ultra small-world" network, and then rewire some edges, or use several small such networks as subgraphs to a larger graph.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small-world properties can arise naturally in social networks and other real-world systems via the process of dual-phase evolution.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This is particularly common where time or spatial constraints limit the addition of connections between vertices The mechanism generally involves periodic shifts between phases, with connections being added during a "global" phase and being reinforced or removed during a "local" phase.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small-world networks can change from scale-free class to broad-scale class whose connectivity distribution has a sharp cutoff following a power law regime due to constraints limiting the addition of new links.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] For strong enough constraints, scale-free networks can even become single-scale networks whose connectivity distribution is characterized as fast decaying.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] It was also shown analytically that scale-free networks are ultra-small, meaning that the distance scales according to $L\propto \log \log N$ .
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The advantages to small world networking for social movement groups are their resistance to change due to the filtering apparatus of using highly connected nodes, and its better effectiveness in relaying information while keeping the number of links required to connect a network to a minimum.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The small world network model is directly applicable to affinity group theory represented in sociological arguments by William Finnegan.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Affinity groups are social movement groups that are small and semi-independent pledged to a larger goal or function.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Though largely unaffiliated at the node level, a few members of high connectivity function as connectivity nodes, linking the different groups through networking.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This small world model has proven an extremely effective protest organization tactic against police action.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Clay Shirky argues that the larger the social network created through small world networking, the more valuable the nodes of high connectivity within the network.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The same can be said for the affinity group model, where the few people within each group connected to outside groups allowed for a large amount of mobilization and adaptation.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A practical example of this is small world networking through affinity groups that William Finnegan outlines in reference to the 1999 Seattle WTO protests.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Many networks studied in geology and geophysics have been shown to have characteristics of small-world networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Networks defined in fracture systems and porous substances have demonstrated these characteristics.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The seismic network in the Southern California region may be a small-world network.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The examples above occur on very different spatial scales, demonstrating the scale invariance of the phenomenon in the earth sciences.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small-world networks have been used to estimate the usability of information stored in large databases.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The measure is termed the Small World Data Transformation Measure.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The greater the database links align to a small-world network the more likely a user is going to be able to extract information in the future.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This usability typically comes at the cost of the amount of information that can be stored in the same repository.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The Freenet peer-to-peer network has been shown to form a small-world network in simulation, allowing information to be stored and retrieved in a manner that scales efficiency as the network grows.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Nearest Neighbor Search solutions like HNSW use small-world networks to efficiently find the information in large item corpuses.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Both anatomical connections in the brain and the synchronization networks of cortical neurons exhibit small-world topology.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Structural and functional connectivity in the brain has also been found to reflect the small-world topology of short path length and high clustering.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The network structure has been found in the mammalian cortex across species as well as in large scale imaging studies in humans.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Advances in connectomics and network neuroscience, have found the small-worldness of neural networks to be associated with efficient communication.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In neural networks, short pathlength between nodes and high clustering at network hubs supports efficient communication between brain regions at the lowest energetic cost.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The brain is constantly processing and adapting to new information and small-world network model supports the intense communication demands of neural networks.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] High clustering of nodes forms local networks which are often functionally related.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Short path length between these hubs supports efficient global communication.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] This balance enables the efficiency of the global network while simultaneously equipping the brain to handle disruptions and maintain homeostasis, due to local subsystems being isolated from the global network.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Loss of small-world network structure has been found to indicate changes in cognition and increased risk of psychological disorders.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] In addition to characterizing whole-brain functional and structural connectivity, specific neural systems, such as the visual system, exhibit small-world network properties.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A small-world network of neurons can exhibit short-term memory.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] A computer model developed by Sara Solla had two stable states, a property (called bistability) thought to be important in memory storage.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] An activating pulse generated self-sustaining loops of communication activity among the neurons.
[src:network-science/small-world-network] The pulses switched the system between stable states: flow (recording a "memory"), and stasis (holding it).
[src:network-science/small-world-network] Small world neuronal networks have also been used as models to understand seizures.
